Chive Velouté 

For pierogi / varenyky service

Ingredients

• 1 tbsp unsalted butter
• 1 tbsp shallot, very finely minced
• 1 tbsp all-purpose flour
• 1 cup good-quality chicken or vegetable stock, kept hot
• 2 tbsp heavy cream
• 2 tbsp fresh chives, finely sliced
• Fine sea salt, to taste
• Optional: ½ tsp lemon juice or white wine vinegar

⸻

Method

Build the velouté base
Melt butter over low–medium heat in a small saucepan. Add shallot and sweat gently until fully soft and translucent, with absolutely no colour. Add flour and cook, stirring constantly, for 60 seconds to remove raw flour flavour while keeping the roux pale.

Incorporate stock
Whisk in hot stock gradually until smooth. Bring to a gentle simmer and cook 2–3 minutes, just until lightly thickened and glossy. The texture should coat the back of a spoon but remain fluid.

Finish off-heat
Stir in cream and immediately remove from heat.

Add chives at once. Blend immediately until completely smooth and vividly green. Pass through a fine chinois or sieve without pressing solids.

Season with fine salt. If using acidity, add lemon juice or vinegar only at the end, drop by drop, tasting continuously.

⸻

Target Texture

Silky, fluid, lightly nappant. Should pool cleanly without spreading uncontrollably.

⸻

Use

Apply sparingly: thin pool, brushed streak, or controlled spooning. The sauce should frame and lift the pierogi, never coat or weigh them down.

⸻

Technical Notes

• Chives must be added off-heat to preserve chlorophyll, aroma, and freshness.
• Cream provides roundness only; the velouté structure comes from the roux.
• Acidity is optional and precise—never dominant.
• This sauce is designed to complement potato and cheese fillings without masking them.
